This map visualizes the Rent Burden Index across Philadelphia’s census tracts, which measures the percentage of renter households spending 30% or more of their income on rent. Higher rent burden is concentrated in West, Southwest, and North Philadelphia, highlighting areas where housing affordability pressures are most severe.

A choropleth approach was used to clearly show spatial patterns in rent burden, making it easier to identify clusters of high and low burden. Residential tracts are color-coded based on rent burden, while non-residential areas (such as parks and airports) are shown in gray.

This visualization provides insight into the geographic distribution of housing cost stress across the city, which can inform policymakers and community organizations working to address housing affordability.
